               &lt;td&gt;&lt;img alt="Photograph of OHA Deputy Director of Behavioral Health Christa Jones speaks at the ceremony" class="govd_template_image" src="https://content.govdelivery.com/attachments/fancy_images/ORHA/2025/11/12645605/6538234/05-stabilization-center-11-03-25-1_crop.jpg" style="border:none; float:left; line-height:1; max-width:100%; outline:none; width:271px" /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
          &lt;/tr&gt;
     &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:10px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,sans-serif"&gt;OHA Deputy Director of Behavioral Health Christa Jones speaks at the ceremony alongside Gov. Kotek and Clackamas County officials, highlighting Oregon&rsquo;s ongoing commitment to expanding behavioral health care access. The Clackamas County Stabilization Center will provide 24/7 behavioral health services for people in crisis.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&ldquo;Today, we are celebrating meaningful access to services that are too often out of reach,&rdquo; Governor Tina Kotek said during the ribbon cutting ceremony on Monday.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&ldquo;Of course, there is still a long way to go and we have to keep pushing to get Oregonians the treatment they need and deserve. I&rsquo;ve made it a priority in my administration to work towards an Oregon where every person can access the care they need, when they need it, and how they need it.&rdquo;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Clackamas County officials and OHA Deputy Director of Behavioral Health Christa Jones joined Governor Kotek at the ceremony.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&ldquo;It&rsquo;s inspiring to see a place where people in crisis can feel safer and supported,&rdquo; Jones said. &ldquo;The thoughtful design, with calming spaces and views of the creek, reflects a deep respect for the dignity and comfort of those receiving care.&rdquo;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The new center is funded through House Bill 5204, passed in 2024 to expand access to behavioral health crisis care through investments in infrastructure. The Clackamas project received $4 million through the Oregon Department of Administrative Services.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Clackamas County Stabilization Center will provide care to adults experiencing a behavioral health crisis and co-occurring disorders. Among the center&rsquo;s services are crisis assessment, short-term housing, peer support, and connections to long-term treatment, recovery resources, and stable housing for individuals in behavioral health crises.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;OHA is committed to transforming the state&rsquo;s behavioral health system, expanding access to services and support, and investing in community-based services that provide compassionate and culturally responsive care.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Clackamas Stabilization Center will serve as an important role by helping residents access services and support in their community.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;More information about the new Clackamas County Stabilization Center is available at:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="http://www.clackamas.us/h3s/stabilization-center?utm_medium=email&amp;amp;utm_source=govdelivery" rel="noopener" style="color: rgb(6, 66, 118); text-decoration-line: none; text-size-adjust: 100%;" target="_blank"&gt;www.clackamas.us/h3s/stabilization-center&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

